<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,655,1242]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,384,655,681]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
This small species can be recognized by the deeply excised mandibles that are oblique apically (
<figureCitation box="[262,351,693,719]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 31" captionStartId="13.[151,274,1360,1384]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1326]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,194,1338]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 31. Head, anterior view. 25. Sphaeropthalma. megagnathos; 26. S. mendica; 27. S. pallida; 28. S. sublobata; 29. S. tetracuspis; 30. S. triangularis; and 31. S. yumaella." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196850/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
Fig. 
<number box="[318,351,693,719]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
), a marginal cell that is approximate the same length as the stigma, the mesosternum lacks processes, the first metasomal segment is sessile with the second, plumose setal fringes are absent on the metasoma, and the cuspis of the genitalia is very short just barely surpassing the free length of the penis valve (Fig. 
<number box="[214,247,805,831]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="61.0">61</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
